This was very hard to narrow down all the amazing places Iâve been and to categorise them but this is my opinion from my experiencesð

BEST POWDER - Cortina in Japan and Kicking Horse in Canada. Iâve had hundreds of powder days but some of the best days of my life were spent at these resorts.
BEST RESORT- Whistler in Canada is tough to top as itâs so big and has everything and anything
MOST PICTURESQUE- Chamonix in France is truly breathtaking. From the town to all the resorts. Views are everywhere! 
BEST FOOD- Hakuba in Japan has some amazing traditional dishes along with western meals. 
BEST FESTIVAL- Snowmachine in Hakuba is a 3 day festival with amazing djâs. Playing on the slopes to the main stage in town.
BEST NIGHTLIFE- Whistler and Banff in Canada are such beautiful towns with plenty of cool bars and some clubs
BEST CHRISTMAS- Big White in Canada and Chamonix in France make you feel like your in the North Pole
BEST FAMILY- Big White in Canada is very family friendly and ski in ski out mountain which is super convenient 
UNDERATED- Silver Star in Canada and Myoko in Japan are exceptional resorts for not having a huge hype
GRARLY TERRAIN- Chamonix in France has the steepest and most wild terrain Iâve ever seen. Definitely advanced ski resorts (still has green runs for learning)

Sory SanlÃ©âs vintage portraits of Burkina Fasoâs people in newly independent West Africa

Sory SanlÃ©: Volta Photo 1965-85 is a fascinating collection of black and white photographic work by Sory SanlÃ©, an eminent portrait photographer from Burkina Faso, the landlocked country in West Africa formerly colonised by the French, then known as Republique de Haute-Volta. 

Written By: Katy Cowan
15 September 2017

Born in 1943 in the Nianiagara district of Bobo-Dioulasso, the countryâs cultural and socio-economic hub, Sory began his career in photography in 1960 â the same year his country regained its independence. Working as an apprentice to a Ghanaian photographer, he learned to process and print the photographs he took with his Rolleiflex twin lens camera.
He began documenting the city on his motorbike, capturing its centuries-old traditions and evolving identity in the wake of African independence. He worked as a freelance reporter, on official assignments, and illustrating record sleeves, but his real passion was studio work. 
In 1960 Sory opened his own portrait studio in Bobo-Dioulasso under the name, Volta Photo, where he photographed the cityâs inhabitants. He shot them with original wit, energy and passion â men, women, young, old, confident, vulnerable, elegant, carefree â while capturing the natural fusion between tradition and modernity. His work conveys a youthful exuberance in the wake of the first decades of African independence. In many ways, his subjects also illustrate the remoteness and melancholy of African cities landlocked deep in the heart of the continent. The powerful poignancy with which SanlÃ© captured his subjects at this particular moment and place in time is what distinguishes him from his contemporaries.
Sory SanlÃ©: Volta Photo 1965-85 is available in a stunning new book dedicated to Sory SanlÃ©âs photography

documenting Shibuyaâs sleeping meltdown with @shibuyameltdown

For over 10 years, the instagram page @shibuyameltdown has been posting a rarely documented side of Japan.

The scenes of tired & drunk salaryman passing out in the streets of Shibuya present a stark contrast.â¨â¨On one side, they highlight the safety of Tokyoâs streets, where youâd probably wake up with most of your belongings neatly beside you, even a water bottle or two from a kind stranger.â¨â¨On the other hand it highlights Japanâs toxic corporate work culture, showing how weekly nomikai sessions leave exhausted salarymen passed out on the streets of Shibuya instead of their beds at home.

This is part of a 5 minute or so interview I did about the older parts of Tokyo (and Japan in general) that I predominantly shoot. 

Being on the other side of the camera is hypocritically not something I feel all that comfortable with, but it was interesting to talk a little about what I like to photograph.

Also, the location it was filmed in turned out be a very apt choice, as where I was sat, and most of whatâs in the video, has now been demolished. An aspect that in many ways says way more than I could ever hope to articulate. So if that sounds interesting, or if the clip makes you want to see more, Iâve included a link to the full version in my profile.

Comment EGG to get the full recipe! Tea Eggs are my favorite childhood snacks. As soon as you walk into a 7-Eleven in Taiwan, you can smell the aromatics from tea eggs. Tea eggs are hard-boiled eggs that are gently cracked and then simmered in a savory mixture of tea, soy sauce, and spices. The flavors slowly seep into the eggs creating a beautiful marble or spider web like pattern. Not only are they so pretty, tea eggs also make a great high protein and low calorie snack or a perfect addition to a simple meal!

Ingredients:
10-12 Tea Eggs
3 cups water
3 black tea bags
1/4 cup light soy sauce
4 tbsp dark soy sauce
1 cinnamon stick
3 star anise
4 dried chili 
3 bay leaves
1-2 tbsp rock sugar 

Directions:
1. Boil the Eggs: Place the eggs in a pot and cover them with cold water. Bring the water to a boil. Bring down to a simmer, cover the pot with a lid, and let it simmer for another 10 minutes. Once cooked, remove the eggs and place them in a bowl of ice water to cool down. 
2. Once the eggs are cool enough to touch, gently crack the shells with the back of a spoon. 
3. In a large pot, add the cracked eggs, water, light soy sauce, dark soy sauce, cinnamon, star anise, dried chili, bay leaves, rock sugar, and black tea bags. 
4. Bring the tea mixture to a boil, then reduce to a simmer. Let the eggs simmer for at least 2 hours. The long they simmer, the more intense flavor and color. Alternatively, you can leave the eggs soaked in the tea mixture overnight or 24 hours before serving.

Mexico and its terrain are vast and incredibly diverse. It has a rich history that one can spend a lifetime studying.  For many immigrants, like my father, who left Mexico at a young age for a better life, traveling and exploring their homeland is a privilege not afforded by many. 
I realized this when I had my daughter, and I decided with my husband that we would take her to explore Mexico. We decided to invite my dad because he, too, needs to explore Mexico.

Before we left for Oaxaca, he asked me, âDenise, Que comen en Oaxaca (what do they eat in Oaxaxa)?â His question confirms the diversity of Mexican cuisine and the lack of exposure to many foods and dishes, especially immigrants who left at a young age. 

It was a blessing to travel to Oaxaca with my viejito and daughter. I hope he can enjoy more of these exploration trips to his homeland, Mexico. 

Oh, and he couldn't get enough of the chocolate and enjoyed one multiple times a day. ð 

Where in Mexico would you take your parents to and why?

From Priest to Luchador: The Real-Life Inspiration Behind Nacho Libre

The cult classic film "Nacho Libre" might seem like pure comedic fiction, but the heart of the story comes from a very real person - Father Sergio GutiÃ©rrez BenÃ­tez.  Known by his wrestling persona "Fray Tormenta" (Friar Storm), BenÃ­tez wasn't just a priest; he was a masked luchador who moonlighted in the ring to raise money for his orphanage.

Born in 1945, BenÃ­tez dedicated his life to the church. However, his calling to help others extended beyond the walls of the clergy.  He founded an orphanage named "La Casa Hogar de los Cachorros de Fray Tormenta" (Fray Tormenta's Home for Puppies), which at times housed over 270 children.

To support this endeavor, BenÃ­tez donned a red and yellow mask and entered the world of lucha libre. Fray Tormenta's wrestling career spanned over two decades, thrilling audiences with his athleticism and dedication.  His identity remained a secret for many years, until it was accidentally revealed.

Even after semi-retiring from wrestling in 2011, BenÃ­tez continued his work at the orphanage.  His legacy lives on through both the children he cared for and "Fray Tormenta Jr.," a former resident inspired to follow in his footsteps.  The story of Sergio GutiÃ©rrez BenÃ­tez is a testament to the power of faith, compassion, and a well-placed flying elbow drop.

Mexican Frijoles (â¬ï¸)
Mexican Food 101

Frijoles de Olla
Serves 2

Ingredients:
250g Frijol 
1/4 Onion
1 Garlic Clove
1tsp Neutral Oil
1tsp Salt
A bunch of epazote leaves (optional)

1 - Leave the frijoles in water overnight.
2 - Strain and rinse the frijoles.
3 - In a pot add 800ml of water, bring it to a boil, and add the salt, frijoles, garlic, and onion.
4 - Reduce the heat to low and let it cook for 2h.
5 - (Optional) Once cooked add the epazote and cook for another 30min.
6 - Plate and enjoy!

Note: I leave epazote as optional because it is often difficult to find outside of Mexico. Due to its strong flavor I know people that like it and others that hate it. The traditional method would be with epazote.

Ike Turner: make them feel mom's labor pains.
Technique can only take you so far. It's impressive, but it won't touch people's souls by itself. Technique is a vehicle, nothing more. 

Think about players like B.B. King, George Harrison, David Gilmour, Keith Richards. These guys aren't flashy, but they can move you with a single note.

-- 

Ike Turner grew up in the Delta Blues' ground zero, Clarksdale, Mississippi.

He wrote and performed what is widely considered the first Rock and Roll song "Rocket 88". (That recording took place at Memphis Recording Service, which eventually became the famous Sun Studios, "The Birthplace of Rock and Roll.") 

Ike bounced all over the South performing in clubs and leading bands. 

While performing in St. Louis, Ike met a young aspiring performer named Ann Bullock. Ike invited her to sing a song with his group, and she knocked everyone out. She joined his group soon afterward and later changed her name to Tina Turner. Ike and Tina's marriage was famously rocky and abusive. But the Ike and Tina Turner Review became world famous and had a massive impact on Rock and Roll.

She wanted a cuddle in the end ðð¥°

KERA MAGAZINE: An Ode to Japanâs Street Style Bible

The rise and fall of KERA magazine mirror the evolution of Harajuku, a creatively influential hub in the 1990s that left a notable mark on Japanese fashion. Over time, this cherished district gained international attention, attracting enthusiasts from all over the globe. Subcultures like Lolita or Visual Kei dominated the streets of Harajuku back in the days. Some of them dressed based on the Punk and Rock scene in the west and embraced extreme, bold, and unconventional styles, emphasizing individuality and pleading for uniqueness. This bubble served as the birthplace for the notorious KERA magazine in 1997. Originally titled âKEROUAC,â the print alluded to Jack Kerouac and his widely known novel âOn the Road,â a cornerstone of the American social and literary Beat movement in the 1950s.

In the subsequent years, the monthly publication gained international popularity, extending their coverage to street styles in fashion capitals like New York and London. The printâs success seemed unstoppable to that point, yet, quietly, a shift in the overall approach to fashion in the scenic Harajuku district has crept in through the back door.

Eventually, in 2017, KERA print was discontinued, alongside with the iconic FRUiTS magazine. When Shoichi Aoki, former editor-in-chief for FRUiTS, reflected on the suspension, he incidentally stated that there were simply âno cool kidsâ around to take photographs of anymore. Though Aoki might be right in his own subjective perception, the background, in fact, appears to be more complex than that.

I forgot to post these Akihabara photos last year when the shop in the first two photos closed, but when passing by recently, I was reminded how special it was, and how different the place is without the owner and his nearby neighbour.

The shop and its accompanying business was founded in 1959, but the man who was running it sadly died, so at the age of 25, his son took over, and for the following 43 years he sat behind the tiny counter of his similarly small stall.

Along with all the changes in the area around him, Shimayama-san experienced upheavals of his own, as after getting married, he tragically lost his wife to cancer. More recently, he has suffered his own health issues, which, along with the pandemic and his ailing mother, meant retirement was the way to go.

The same decision was also taken by his near neighbour the year before â a lovely old lady whose photos Iâve posted before. That said, at 93 years of age, and working behind the counter for 64 years, she made her fellow shop owner seem like a mere part-timer.

An Akihabara era that is very much coming to and, but thankfully it isnât over just yet, as one last shop from the same generation survives. A bookshop proprietor who, just like her retired pals, has a smile as warm as her shop is small.

Fukaya. Saitama prefecture.

In Fukaya, it is possible to discover a rare site: a cinema in a old sake factory.

Several decades ago, Takeishi, originally from Tokyo, moved to Fukaya, his wife's hometown. Passionate about cinema, the man discovered an old abandoned sake factory. There, a great project was born: to revive the place, by multiplying the activities there, the most important of which would be the opening of a real cinema. For this, Takeishi had to renovate the place. Optimistic and determined, he created an association and collected all the funds. The cinema was born in 2002.

The cinema building has retained its original charm.  Inside, visitors can discover a different programme from other cinemas, with many films rares, engaged, documentaries,  from many countries of the world but also classics. People can give their opinion about the movies to project. Takeishi also bought two old projectors and almost two hundred old reel-to-reel films in Tokyo. From time to time, the cinema offers the screening of an old film, a treasure to be preserved for the manager.

Inside the old sake factory, there are several valuable buildings. They are also rented out. Several activities accompany the cinema, such as a cafÃ©, a 2nd hand bookstore, local craft shops, and a hall hosts events such as dance performances and workshops.
On the occasion of the twentieth anniversary of the cinema, the association is planning to buy the whole site to ensure its preservation. The site is threatened by a road project.
Because of its architectural character, charm, history and special features, the cinema regularly receives financial support from individuals and even actors and directors. Several years ago, the actress Kirin Kiki came to Fukaya and made a large donation, attracted by the project.

Through its action, the association wishes to revitalise a town affected by numerous abandoned houses and buildings.

Do not hesitate to contact the cinema if you wish to support the project.
